summary.seg: Cambridge, University Library, MS Ii.4.6 contains thirty-six homilies, most of which were written by Ælfric of Eynsham (c. 955–c. 1010), one of the most prolific authors of Late Old English. The majority of the homilies originate from Ælfric's two series of Catholic Homilies, the first complete versions of which were composed between c. 989 and 992. Only two homilies (written for Rogationtide) are anonymous, although they incorporate much Ælfrician material as well. The homilies are organised according to the so-called 'Temporale', a cycle of movable feasts in the liturgical calendar that are keyed to the date of Easter, meaning that they occur in the order of the church year.

The manuscript was copied in the mid-eleventh century at the royal Benedictine abbey of New Minster, Winchester. Subsequently, it may have been owned by Tavistock Abbey in Devon, since a sixteenth-century inscription on fol. 1r claims that it was found at the latter monastery (dissolved in 1539) by Robert Farrar [Ferrers], agent to Francis Russell (1526/7–1585), 2nd Earl of Bedford, in 1566. The earl presented the manuscript to Archbishop Matthew Parker (1504–1575) in 1567, who, in turn, donated it to the University of Cambridge in 1574.

Ælfric's Catholic Homilies are found in a large number of manuscripts originating from a period that spans from the end of the tenth century until c. 1200. According to John C. Pope, CUL Ii.4.6 is related to two other manuscripts, namely, Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 302 (c. 1100–1110) and London, British Library, Cotton MS Faustina A IX (c. 1100–1150). Pope argues that all three manuscripts ultimately derive from a common exemplar.

The manuscript is missing several folios at the beginning and currently runs from the second Sunday after Epiphany until the first Sunday after Pentecost, ending with two extra homilies for Rogationtide. Considering that there are manuscripts that not only feature more complete collections of the Catholic Homilies but were also produced close to their original date of composition (such as London, British Library, Royal MS 7 C XII from 990; and Cambridge, University Library, MS Gg.3.28 from c. 1000), one may wonder what the relevance is of manuscripts such as CUL Ii.4.6. However, their particular importance lies in the fact that medieval texts were not static entities, like published texts are today. Ælfric continually updated his homilies throughout his lifetime, and CUL Ii.4.6 represents a distinct stage in their development. The manuscript, for instance, features a version of the first series' homily for the second Sunday after Easter (Homily 17) that is much longer than other copies, and is thought to contain an authentic addition by Ælfric. Manuscripts such as CUL Ii.4.6 thus can be invaluable for studying how Ælfric developed his work over a long period of time and may feature authorial changes that scholars would miss if they only researched the most complete and earlier manuscripts.

Moreover, the study of later Ælfrician manuscripts can tell us something about the reception of his homilies by later audiences. For instance, readers used symbols to highlight passages which they thought were important or added interlinear or marginal material. Indeed, CUL Ii.4.6 contains a number of contemporary glosses and additions, in particular on fols 23v–37r, and also some marginal annotations from c. 1300 on fols 132r, 146r, and 146v. Most notably, the later annotations, according to N. R. Ker, 'refer to the [Old English] text and show understanding of it'.

Another type of response is not so easily discernible, namely, the replacement of linguistic features and lexical items during the process of copying the text. In some twelfth-century manuscripts containing the Catholic Homilies, scribes have changed case endings and replaced words, most likely because they considered these to be obsolete. These alterations are incredibly valuable for our knowledge of the development of the English language during the twelfth century, which is traditionally seen as the transitional period between Old and Middle English. Manuscripts such as CUL Ii.4.6 can therefore shed light on the development of Ælfric’s Catholic Homilies, give insight into the homilies’ reception by later audiences, and enable us to learn more about that fascinating period in the history of English when Old English gave way to Middle English.

Amos van Baalen
Leiden University Centre for Linguistics

extent.seg:
ii + 6 + 1, i, 148, ii, 147, ii, 1, i, 1, ii + i + xvi + i + ii leaves.
The manuscript opens with eight endleaves, two added to the volume when it was most recently bound and six added when it was bound in the 16th century (see Binding for further details). From that point onwards, the medieval portion of the manuscript begins, however leaves were added in various places during the 16th century in order to supply space for a table of contents, a printed accompaniment to part of the text, or text missing through the loss of leaves. These different leaves have been enumerated above and distinguished from the medieval leaves by commas. The plus sign separates this medieval section from the various endleaves or added leaves that precede or follow it. (See Part 2's Additions for further details of the contents of some of these).
Two unfoliated paper stubs are present after f. 21, in place of two excised leaves, and were added in order to secure the binding of the two leaves (ff. 16-17) that were originally conjoint with them. Being stubs rather than partial leaves, they are not included in this statement of extent. However, since one of them does contain a 19th/20th-century annotation in pencil, they have been assigned numbers for the purpose of this digital record (see Foliation).

foliation.note: Written in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.
Two paper stubs after f. 21 are not foliated, but have been assigned the numbers [21a] and [21b] for the purposes of this record.

Two printed pages were added to the manuscript in the 16th century but were not numbered as part of this foliation sequence: they are numbered here as ff. [156a-156b]. One leaf was accidentally omitted from the sequence, after f. 241, and was later marked as f. 241a.
The sequence runs slightly out of order at the end of the manuscript, owing to the rearrangement of the leaves when the manuscript was last rebound (see Binding).
Written in ink in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos only. Linked to the table of contents added to f. 8r.
Continued for the rear endleaves, written in pencil by the same or similar hand responsible for the 20th-century foliation.

collation.p:
The manuscript comprises mostly quires of 8 leaves, except for a group of four quires of ten leaves near the beginning (Quires 3-6). In many of the quires, a bifolium has been formed from two singletons: in Quire 3, the 4th and 7th leaves; and in Quires 15-16, 19-20, 23, 25, 27-33 and 37, the 3rd and 6th leaves.
Quire 18+1 (ff. 7-15: 1st leaf reversed; 16th-century leaf, f. 8, added after 1st leaf)
Quire 28-2 (ff. 16-21: 7th-8th leaves excised, after f. 21; probably blank)
Quires 3-610 (ff. 22-61)
Quires 7-368 (ff. 62-300)
Quire 378-3+3 (ff. 301-308: 4th, 5th and 7th leaves missing, replaced by 16th-century leaves, ff. 304, 305 and 307
Two 16th-century leaves (ff. 309-310: added to supply missing text)
collation.formula: 18+1 (2nd leaf added) 28-2 (7th-8th leaves excised, probably blank) 3-610 7-368 378-3+3 (4th, 5th and 7th leaves missing, later replaced)

note.p: 'Index sermonum' added to f. 8r in the 16th-century. Further hands have annotated this, including that of Abraham Wheelock (see below) and another that may be John Mitchell KembleKemble, John M. (John Mitchell), 1807-1857, who added interlinear notes comparing the manuscript's contents to that of Cambridge, University Library, MS Gg.3.28 (for an example of Kemble's hand, see Cambridge, University Library, MS Gg.5.35.

Notes towards an alphabetical index, on 17th-century paper endleaves (ff. 313-328) and a 16th-century parchment endleaf (f. 312r) at the back of the manuscript, probably added and begun by Wheelocke, Abraham, 1593-1653 Abraham Wheelocke (c. 1593-1653), University Librarian 1629-53, but containing additions by numerous other hands of the 17th and possibly 18th centuries.

Annotations in pencil, again by Wheelocke, Abraham, 1593-1653 Abraham Wheelocke , throughout the manuscript. See, for example, ff. 8r, 16v-20v, 23r-30v (the last in the top margin and heavily rubbed), etc.

binding.p: Bound in wooden boards, quarter red leather with blind-tooled interlace pattern on the front and rear covers and blind-tooled zig-zag patterning on the top and bottom edges. Stamped 'D.C. & Son 1928': i.e. Douglas Cockerell and SonDouglas Cockerell and Son (Firm).
Between 1926 and 1930, M.R. James prepared a description of the manuscript (now UA ULIB 7/3/74/45), at which point it was disbound.
Contents inked onto the fore-edge by Wheelocke, Abraham, 1593-1653 Abraham Wheelocke : 'Homiliae 34 Saxon. vide pag. 297'

Evidence preserved within the manuscript (endleaves bearing four friction-holes and rust stains, suggesting the presence formerly of four corner-bosses and a chain staple, and a title label preserved on f. 6r) indicates that the manuscript was previously bound in similar style to that of the binding on other manuscripts donated to the University Library by Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 Matthew Parker (for an example, see: MS Ii.2.4).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1574 by Matthew Parker (1504-1575), archbishop of Canterbury Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575. No. 9 in the list of 25 'Libri Scripti in pergameno' published to commemorate Parker's gift (see Early catalogues of manuscripts, up to c. 1600. Donation inscription on f. 9v: 'Matthaeus Cantuar: dedit 1574'.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1926 and 1930 by M.R. James James, M.R. (Montague Rhodes), 1862-1936, now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/74) and the description of the manuscript published by N.R. Ker, Catalogue of manuscripts containing Anglo-Saxon (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1957).

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

msItem.note: According to Ker (1957): 'ff. 1-3, 6, 311-12 [are] portions of a sixteenth-century document, apparently a dispute about the will of William Wiker of Chale (Isle of Wight), of which Richard, abbot of Quarr (Richard Tottenham, abbot 1508-21), was an executor. msItem.author: Ælfric
msItem.title: Feria III. De Dominica oratione
msItem.incipit: 299r Se hælend crist syþþan he to þisum lífe cóm
msItem.explicit: 308v eallum cristenum manuum gelíce
msItem.note: Folio 303 ends 'Syle ús nu to dæg úrne' (Thorpe (1844), p. 264 l. 31), after which two leaves are missing.
Folio 306 contains 'on þære fándunge...swiðe rihtlice' (Thorpe (1844), pp. 268 l. 11-270 l. 1), after which one leaf is missing.
Folio 308 contains 'to þisum lífe...mannum gelíce' (Thorpe (1844), pp. 270 l. 27-272 l. 18).
The missing portions of the homily were supplied in the 16th century on ff. 304-305, 307 and 309-310.

list.item: Quire 18+1 (ff. 7-15: 1st leaf reversed; 16th-century leaf, f. 8, added after 1st leaf)
Quire 28-2 (ff. 16-21: 7th-8th leaves excised, after f. 21; probably blank)
Quire 378-3+3 (ff. 301-308: 4th, 5th and 7th leaves missing, replaced by 16th-century leaves, ff. 304, 305 and 307
Two 16th-century leaves (ff. 309-310: added to supply missing text)

condition.p: Off-set from recycled endleaves obscuring text on f. 7r and staining of f. 9r where it had previously been pasted to f. 8v

Occasional (and original) small faults in the parchment (for example, ff. 9, 14, 15, 99, 122, 124 (x2), 135 (x4), 136, etc. Larger faults show evidence of having been stitched closed, sewing now gone (for example, ff. 144, 202, 290)
Two paper stubs between ff. 21 and 22, added when the manuscript was rebound in order to secure the remaining counterpart leaves.
Old parchment repair to irregular bottom edge of f. 124. Irregular bottom edge on ff. 151, 159, 219.

Fore-edge margin and outer edge of the text block lost from f. 268. Also lost from f. 306, replaced by old (16th-century?) parchment repair and missing text written in. Fore-edge margin lost from f. 308, text not affected; old parchment repair to the page (again, perhaps 16th-century).

p.seg: Ruled in hardpoint, frame and line. Single columns, 20 lines to the page, written above top line.

handNote.p: Written by two hands in Insular minuscule.

According to Ker (1957): 'In two upright black rather ugly hands, the second and larger beginning at f. 148r and continuing to the end and writing also ff. 7, 9-21 (Quires 1-2): ð prominent: in the second hand e is sometimes high in the combination æ, the head of long s is sometimes prolonged upwards and looped and the ends of descenders are seriffed: hyphens are written by the first hand only and are placed a little way out in the margins at the beginning as well as at the end of lines.'

decoNote.p: Plain initials in green, red or blue.
From f. 148r (where the second scribal hand begins), the first line of a homily is often written in handsome majuscule letters, alternately red and green or red and black.

note.p: Subdivisions of the text are sometimes marked by 'K' in the margin by a near-/contemporary hand (e.g. f. 100).

Alternate wording provided by a near-/contemporary hand in interlinear glosses on ff. 23v ('uel gerƿicð' - above 'neablinð', which appears to be a correction written by a different hand over an erasure), 24v ('uel geornfulre'), 26r ('uel geornfullnysse'), 26v ('heofonan rices myrliðe' and 'uel crist'), 27r ('uel heofonan rices'), 28v ('uel deofla'), etc.
Interlinear corrections on ff. 46r, 217. Correction over erasure on f. 75v.
Marginal annotations referring to the text and demonstrating an understanding of it, written by a 13th/14th-century hand: see ff. 132r, 146r, 146v.

Several rubrics added to the manuscript by a later, perhaps 16th-century hand, writing in imitation of the insular minuscule used in the text (for example, ff. 9v, 175r, 180v). The same hand also made a correction to f. 37r.

Fabric static page-marker added to f. 156, probably while the manuscript was in Matthew Parker's hands: similar markers were added to other books in his possession (see, for example, Cambridge, University Library, MS Ff.1.23).

Two leaves (four printed pages; the reverse is blank) from Matthew Parker's Testimonie of antiquitie (1566?) have been added between ff. 156 and 157, together with marginal annotations referring to them on f. 156v.

Opening of homilies accompanied by numbers written in pencil in the margins - e.g. §1 (f. 9v), §2 (f. 18v), etc - corresponding with the itemisation of the manuscript's contents in the Catalogue of manuscripts preserved the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 3 (1858).
Quire numbers added in pencil by a modern hand to the recto of the first leaf of each quire.

The word 'beginning' written by a 19th/20th-century hand onto f. [21b] verso, the second of two paper stubs added in the place of two excised leaves after f. 21, in order to secure the binding of ff. 16-17, the two remaining conjoint leaves.

origin.p: Written at New Minster, WinchesterNew Minster, Winchester.

provenance.p: Found at Tavistock Abbey Tavistock Abbey in 1566 (and presumably owned by the abbey prior to that). See inscription on f. 1r: 'Hunc codicem cum altero consimili: reperit R. Ferror seruus comitis Bedfordie in Domo quondam cenobio de Tavestocke in Devinshire, Ao 1566' (repeated on f. 311v with minor differences).
Owned by Robert Farrar/Ferrers (d. 1572/76?) Farrar/Ferrers, Robert (d. 1572/76?), member of parliament for Tavistock (see History of Parliament online): mentioned in above inscription.

Owned by Francis Russell (b. 1526/27, d. 1585), 2nd earl of Bedford Bedford, Francis Russell, Earl of, 1526 or 1527-1585: see inscriptions on f. 7v ('F. Bedford') and f. 308v ('Franciscus Comes Bedfordius 1566').

Given by Russell Bedford, Francis Russell, Earl of, 1526 or 1527-1585 to Matthew Parker (1504-1575), archbishop of Canterbury Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 on 29th December 1567: see inscription on f. 308v ('Dedit Matthæo Cantuar 29o Decembris Ano 1567o in camera stellata' - i.e. in Star Chamber).
